{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 Calibri;}{\f1 Courier New;}}\paperw11907\paperh16840\margl1440\margr1440\margt1080\margb1080\fs22 Employee Payroll Processor\line \line Assignment Information\line Dar es Salaam Institute of Technology\line Civil Engineering Department\line Module: Programming Fundamentals for Technicians (GST 05117)\line Class: OD24CE-2 | Assignment Type: Group | Assignment No: 3\line Group Number: 11 | Submission Date: March 1, 2026\line \line Group Members\line 1. ABDULAZIZ MAHYORO (240121429579)\line 2. LAWRENCE MMATAMBWE (220121417491)\line 3. ELIAH HANGO (240121476067)\line 4. HUSSEIN OMARY (240121449049)\line 5. ROBERT JAMES (240121479897)\line 6. GIDEON OLANG'U (240121429421)\line 7. MOSES MFUSE (24012317533)\line 8. GLORIA DAUDI (240121453512)\line \line Brief Explanation (One-Page Summary)\line This mini project was prepared by Group 11 to practice core C programming skills in a direct and practical way. The main goal is to let a user enter data, process that data logically, and get a clear output report.\line In this project (Employee Payroll Processor), payroll calculator that computes overtime, tax, and net salary for multiple employees.\line \line How the Program Works\line 1. It shows a clear prompt/menu to the user.\line 2. It accepts and validates user input to avoid wrong values.\line 3. It processes data using conditions, loops, and calculations.\line 4. It prints final results in a readable format.\line \line Concepts Practiced\line - Functions\line - Structs and arrays\line - Arithmetic operators\line - Conditionals\line - Input validation\line \line Sample Output (short example)\line === Employee Payroll Processor ===\line 1. Add Employee Payroll Record\line 2. View Payroll Report\line 3. Exit\line Choose an option: 1\line Enter employee ID: 101\line Enter employee name: Jane Doe\line Enter base salary: 1000\line \line Presentation Note\line This mini project is intentionally simple, focused, and easy to explain during presentation.}